description:
In main.c init_standalone_lora() at lines 110-133:
```c
eui64 = lichen_lora_l2_get_eui64();
if (eui64 == NULL) {
    LOG_ERR("main: failed to get EUI-64");
    goto cleanup;
}
...
cleanup:
    lichen_lora_l2_stop();
    lichen_lora_l2_deinit();
    return (ret < 0) ? ret : -ENODATA;
```

When eui64 is NULL, we goto cleanup. At this point, ret is 0 (from successful lichen_lora_l2_start at line 104). So the function returns -ENODATA.

This is actually correct behavior - -ENODATA is an appropriate error when EUI-64 is not available. The '(ret < 0) ? ret : -ENODATA' pattern ensures that if we jumped to cleanup from an earlier error (where ret < 0), we preserve that error code; otherwise we return -ENODATA.

NO BUG - the logic is correct.
